16:22.415 --> 16:31.657 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Death rates in
the United States have declined
steadily for decades. But a

16:31.657 --> 16:36.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
study out this week found a
disturbing reversal in mortality
rates for white Americans
between

16:36.963 --> 16:42.802 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the ages of 45 and 54 who do
not hold a college degree.

16:42.802 --> 16:48.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For that group, the rate of
death has climbed since 1999,
even as rates for people of
different

16:48.908 --> 16:55.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ages, races and education levels
have continued to fall. The
causes of death driving the
reversal

16:55.748 --> 17:03.489 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were suicide, alcohol-related
liver diseases, and prescription
opioids and heroin overdoses.

17:03.489 --> 17:08.594 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm joined now by one of the
study's authors, Anne Case. She
is a professor of economics

17:08.594 --> 17:14.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and public affairs at Princeton
University. And by Dante Chinni.
He's a data reporter

17:14.567 --> 17:19.572 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and he's director of the
American Communities Project, a
political science and journalism

17:19.572 --> 17:23.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
program at Michigan State
University that uses data to
look at social, political and

17:23.676 --> 17:25.778 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
cultural divides.

17:25.778 --> 17:28.414 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And welcome to you both.

17:28.414 --> 17:30.616 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Professor Case, let
me begin with you.

17:30.616 --> 17:35.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have said that when you and
your husband, who is Professor
Angus Deaton -- he's the

17:35.354 --> 17:40.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
winner of this year's Nobel
Prize, and he was the co-author
of this study -- that when

17:40.393 --> 17:47.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you came across these numbers,
you basically stumbled across
this information, and that

17:47.066 --> 17:49.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he said you practically fell out
of your chairs. It was that
surprising?

17:49.936 --> 17:54.006 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANNE CASE, Princeton University:
It is that surprising.

17:54.006 --> 18:00.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After so many decades in which
mortality rates fell at 2
percent a year, and the fact
that

18:00.746 --> 18:05.384 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in all of the sister countries
that we compare ourselves to,
all the wealthy countries of

18:05.384 --> 18:11.223 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Europe and all the
English-speaking countries,
Canada, Australia, New Zealand,
with their

18:11.223 --> 18:14.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mortality rates also falling at
2 percent a year, to suddenly
see this reversal was

18:14.894 --> 18:18.564 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
really stunning.

18:18.564 --> 18:23.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it has been stunning to all
of the medical people, the
epidemiologists that we have
talked

18:23.202 --> 18:25.671 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to as well.

18:25.671 --> 18:30.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It's already --
Professor Case, it's already
being labeled by some as
despair-related

18:30.476 --> 18:35.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
deaths. What is it particularly
about this -- these mortality --
this mortality rate

18:35.381 --> 18:38.384 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that stood out to you?

18:38.384 --> 18:44.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANNE CASE: The fact that there
are several parts of this that
are puzzles that we have

18:44.190 --> 18:51.430 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to dig into further, the fact
that it's men and women,
mortality rates by suicide, by

18:51.430 --> 18:58.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
drug overdose, by
alcohol-related deaths rising
for all of -- for both men and
women, the

18:58.004 --> 19:02.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fact that it's not happening in
the African-American community,
it's not happening in the
Hispanic

19:02.775 --> 19:06.312 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
community, and it's
not happening abroad.

19:06.312 --> 19:12.251 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, all of those things stood
out to us as puzzle pieces that
we have to look into further

19:12.251 --> 19:18.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to figure out, what are the root
causes of this? We know the
proximate causes, drug overdose,

19:18.357 --> 19:22.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
availability of prescription
opioids. But I think the next
round of research will be

19:22.528 --> 19:25.664 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to look at the deeper causes.

19:25.664 --> 19:30.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Dante Chinni, how
does this square with what you
have been seeing as you

19:30.569 --> 19:35.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have looked at the American --
Americans everywhere and as you
think about this cohort we're
talking

19:35.441 --> 19:40.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about, middle-aged Americans,
45-54, white? What have you
seen?

19:40.079 --> 19:43.549 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DANTE CHINNI, American
Communities Project: Well, the
way I look at the country, the
breakdown

19:43.549 --> 19:47.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
we do at the American
Communities Project, is there
are large segments of America
that

19:47.153 --> 19:50.823 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
are made up of large
chunks of this population.

19:50.823 --> 19:57.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, they tend to be rural,
white, not high education
levels, or high school, no
bachelor's

19:57.963 --> 20:03.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or even a community college
degree. And the places those
populations are heavily based

20:03.035 --> 20:08.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are the Bible Belt, what we call
evangelical hubs, the
Appalachian America, which is
what

20:08.674 --> 20:13.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we call working-class country,
and then graying America, which
is kind of more based in the

20:13.379 --> 20:18.150 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
North and the West, but
populations, again, elderly --
more -- I don't want to say
elderly,

20:18.150 --> 20:21.954 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but older people and people
without a lot of college
degrees, overwhelmingly white.

20:21.954 --> 20:25.724 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do we know about those
places? Higher unemployment
rates than the national average,

20:25.724 --> 20:28.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
higher unemployment rates than
other kinds of communities in
the country.

20:28.227 --> 20:31.363 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The other thing that really
sticks out about them is, beyond
the unemployment rate, which

20:31.363 --> 20:35.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can be a little bit deceptive,
there is the work force
participation rate. In these
places,

20:35.367 --> 20:38.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you're talking about all these
communities I just outlined, 44
percent, 45 percent of

20:38.304 --> 20:41.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the population not
in the work force.

20:41.807 --> 20:46.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, look, some of that is
probably due to people have
retired or they want to stay at

20:46.112 --> 20:50.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
home. But I think when you
combine that with the higher
unemployment rates in those
areas,

20:50.883 --> 20:53.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think what you're really
seeing is, in terms of the
difficulty of finding a way to
make

20:53.919 --> 20:55.921 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a living, right?

20:55.921 --> 20:59.258 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a much -- it's a tougher
life in these places now. I
think a lot of this has to do

20:59.258 --> 21:02.761 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with the decline of small
manufacturing in these places.
Tougher rural life.

21:02.761 --> 21:06.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you think
about -- Professor Case, you
think about what's happened in
this

21:06.532 --> 21:10.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
country to the economy over the
last 15 years, we can't, of
course, jump to any conclusions,

21:10.269 --> 21:16.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but we know jobs -- there's been
a huge change in the job
picture.

21:16.242 --> 21:19.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We know American manufacturing
has taken a big hit. What sorts
of questions does all

21:19.979 --> 21:22.882 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this raise for you?

21:22.882 --> 21:29.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE CASE: It's -- one of the
questions is why it is the case
that the
employment-to-population

21:29.088 --> 21:35.094 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ratio has fallen so
dramatically, especially among
women.

21:35.094 --> 21:40.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In our surveys, we were able to
look at morbidity, as well as
mortality, so we can actually
find

21:40.966 --> 21:46.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out how people are, what their
general health is like, what
their mental health is like,

21:46.839 --> 21:53.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and there's been a doubling in
this 15-year period among people
aged 45-54 who report

21:53.512 --> 21:56.815 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that they're unable to work.

21:56.815 --> 22:03.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, this used to be the period
of time when people were at
their highest earnings capacity.

22:03.822 --> 22:09.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And to see these people, upwards
of 10 percent of the white
population, saying that they're

22:09.128 --> 22:13.432 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
not able to work is
really troubling.

22:13.432 --> 22:19.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It used to be the case that,
with a high school degree, you
could get a good job, you could

22:19.038 --> 22:25.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
get a job with benefits, you
could get a job that was stable,
that you had job security.

22:25.844 --> 22:35.487 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think people's narratives
of their own lives had in them
having a job, and the fact

22:35.487 --> 22:42.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that these jobs are gone and
they're not coming back any time
soon leads people to despair.

22:42.928 --> 22:47.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they report themselves in
worse health. They report lower
mental health, a lot more

22:47.466 --> 22:53.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stress, a lot more distress. And
I think these mortality rates
just reflect that.

22:53.505 --> 22:58.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Dante Chinni, I
mean, I -- you're nodding your
head as she's saying all this.

22:58.744 --> 23:04.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, this does seem to
dovetail with at least the
circumstances that you find in
your

23:04.149 --> 23:04.650 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
research.

23:04.650 --> 23:06.619 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DANTE CHINNI: Yes, absolutely.

23:06.619 --> 23:10.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, I can't -- I would love
to get the professor's data and
run a geographic analysis

23:10.789 --> 23:15.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on it to see if we're seeing
these things fall in line with
what I'm expecting. But

23:15.561 --> 23:17.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
this is exactly what
we're talking about.

23:17.796 --> 23:22.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Look, in a lot of these places,
when you lose a job,
particularly if you're in your
40s,

23:22.334 --> 23:24.837 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there's not a lot of places to
go. There's certainly not a lot
of places to go to get

23:24.837 --> 23:28.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a job where you can earn similar
to what you were earning before.
Maybe the benefits go

23:28.040 --> 23:31.310 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
away. Maybe the health
insurance goes away.

23:31.310 --> 23:34.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you go out to some of these
places, not just rural America,
but there's a category

23:34.546 --> 23:39.485 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we look at call the middle
suburbs, and they're based --
they're overwhelmingly white.

23:39.485 --> 23:42.121 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're primarily based in the
Industrial Midwest, the
Northeast, around Pittsburgh,

23:42.121 --> 23:45.557 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Cleveland, Detroit. Milwaukee,
you see some of it.

23:45.557 --> 23:50.763 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You have large white
populations. A lot of these were
high school-educated people who

23:50.763 --> 23:53.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
did make a really good living.
They had a good life. Their
parents had a good life.

23:53.866 --> 23:58.637 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They had a good life. And all of
a sudden, the rules changed,
right? And the idea that

23:58.637 --> 24:00.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a high school education was good
enough, it wasn't good enough
anymore. It wasn't good

24:00.906 --> 24:03.242 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
enough to have the cabin
up north anymore.

24:03.242 --> 24:07.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, suddenly, it wasn't good
enough to have a job anymore.
And that's a very hard thing

24:07.279 --> 24:11.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to deal with. We will see.
Again, we have got to take
another couple cuts at this
data,

24:11.016 --> 24:12.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
right, and see what's there. But
it certainly does fit the
profile.

24:12.885 --> 24:14.987 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

24:14.987 --> 24:17.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, it's clear that there is
going to be more research. At
least, it looks as if there

24:17.990 --> 24:23.228 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is going to be more research
based on what you have done.

24:23.228 --> 24:26.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Professor Case, thank you very
much for joining us. Professor
Anne Case at Princeton and Dante

24:26.999 --> 24:29.902 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Chinni here in Washington,
we appreciate it.

24:29.902 --> 24:33.839 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANTE CHINNI: Thanks.

24:33.839 --> 24:39.978 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANNE CASE: Thanks very much.

24:39.978 --> 24:45.117 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Stay with us.

24:45.117 --> 24:49.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": the
Middle East conflict 20 years
after an Israeli prime
minister's

24:49.922 --> 24:55.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
assassination; and actor Jeff
Daniels trades in the Big Apple
for the Midwest.

24:55.661 --> 25:02.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, first, natural gas is often
considered a cleaner fuel than
coal. It emits about half

25:02.334 --> 25:06.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as much carbon dioxide. But the
main component in natural gas is
another greenhouse gas:

25:06.572 --> 25:09.141 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
methane.

25:09.141 --> 25:14.012 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As special correspondent
Kathleen McCleery explains,
that's why both
environmentalists

25:14.012 --> 25:19.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the energy industry are
trying to find ways to capture
leaks from oil and gas
facilities.

25:19.151 --> 25:23.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: You can't see
it with the naked eye, but
methane gas is escaping into

25:23.989 --> 25:28.026 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the air around this well in
Northwestern New Mexico.

25:28.026 --> 25:34.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: Oh, yes. Yes, boy, it's
just blowing up out of the --
off the side of it here.

25:34.833 --> 25:39.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: You can see
the methane, along with other
emissions, with the help

25:39.571 --> 25:44.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of an infrared camera, this one
operated by the environmental
group Earthworks.

25:44.276 --> 25:49.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: There's a lot of leaking
coming from both of those valve
boxes.

25:49.748 --> 25:54.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: Methane is
the primary component of natural
gas. It's also a greenhouse

25:54.353 --> 25:59.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
gas. Like carbon dioxide, it
traps energy in the atmosphere,
and according to the
Environmental

25:59.291 --> 26:04.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Protection Agency, contributes
to climate change. CO2 is far
more prevalent, but methane

26:04.663 --> 26:06.965 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is much more potent.

26:06.965 --> 26:09.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MANVENDRA DUBEY, Los Alamos
National Laboratory: Methane is
about 25 times more potent a
greenhouse

26:09.868 --> 26:13.138 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
gas on a 100-year
horizon than CO2.

26:13.138 --> 26:18.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: Los Alamos
atmospheric scientist Manvendra
Dubey was measuring carbon

26:18.544 --> 26:24.750 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
dioxide, not methane, last year
when NASA released satellite
images, including this

26:24.750 --> 26:30.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one showing a 2,500-square-mile
hot spot centered over the Four
Corners area, where New Mexico,

26:30.989 --> 26:34.193 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Colorado, Utah and Arizona meet.

26:34.193 --> 26:40.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MANVENDRA DUBEY: They showed
that, over Four Corners, methane
was enhanced. It was the

26:40.265 --> 26:44.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- kind of the hottest methane
spot in the whole of continental
U.S.

26:44.169 --> 26:48.740 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: Now, Dubey
and others are tracking methane
through ground and aerial

26:48.740 --> 26:54.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
investigations aimed at finding
the sources of the hot spot.
Some emissions seep out of

26:54.813 --> 27:00.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coal beds here in the San Juan
Basin. Some come from
agriculture, including cows.
Winds

27:00.452 --> 27:05.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
allow the gas to pool in the
river basin surrounded by
mountains.

27:05.057 --> 27:12.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nationwide, the EPA traces the
largest amount, about 30
percent, to natural gas and
petroleum.

27:12.030 --> 27:16.101 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But the industry doesn't
accept that figure yet.

27:16.101 --> 27:20.339 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Wally Drangmeister, vice
president of the New Mexico Oil
and Gas Association, wants

27:20.339 --> 27:23.876 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the ongoing research to
examine all sources.

27:23.876 --> 27:25.143 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WALLY DRANGMEISTER, Vice
President, New Mexico Oil and
Gas Association: There are
natural

27:25.143 --> 27:29.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
outcroppings. There's coal
mining. There's a lot of other
activities, and so we'd really

27:29.748 --> 27:34.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
like to see the science
completed, so that we're not
just the only industry or the
only

27:34.920 --> 27:37.356 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
source that's getting blamed.

27:37.356 --> 27:42.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE SCHREIBER, New Mexico:
We're in the middle of nowhere,
but, yes, basically, we're kind

27:42.828 --> 27:45.497 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
of in the middle
of that hot spot.

27:45.497 --> 27:50.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: At Devil's
Spring Ranch, Don and Jane
Schreiber worry about the
natural

27:50.536 --> 27:55.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
gas wells on their property.
They took us along on a tour in
their retrofitted school

27:55.407 --> 27:59.311 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
bus when the Earthworks
team visited recently.

27:59.311 --> 28:02.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRUCE BAIZEL, Earthworks: If you
see leakage coming on this
camera, there is leakage, and

28:02.981 --> 28:05.717 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there's really no argument
about it anymore.

28:05.717 --> 28:09.888 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: The
Schreibers' concern goes beyond
climate change to the air
they're

28:09.888 --> 28:14.026 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
breathing, because other
chemicals like benzene are
emitted along with the methane.

28:14.026 --> 28:16.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DON SCHREIBER, New Mexico: It's
got to be bad, and now we know
it is, and it's in that

28:16.929 --> 28:21.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
cloud, and it's a very,
very sobering thing.

28:21.800 --> 28:27.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: Companies can
drill here because of a law
called split estate. The

28:27.472 --> 28:32.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Schreibers own the land above
ground, but the mineral rights
below, in this case owned

28:32.344 --> 28:37.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by the federal government, can
be leased to oil and gas
companies.

28:37.115 --> 28:42.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
More than 120 wells dot the
Schreibers' ranch, just a
fraction of the tens of
thousands in

28:42.354 --> 28:45.924 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the nation's second largest
natural gas field.

28:45.924 --> 28:53.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE SCHREIBER: We went to three
wells today. Every one of them
were either venting or leaking.

28:53.365 --> 28:57.135 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And those were, you know, less
than a mile from our house.

28:57.135 --> 29:02.207 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DON SCHREIBER: Well, there are
20,000 existing wells here now,
most of them acting just exactly

29:02.207 --> 29:05.844 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
like the wells we saw today.

29:05.844 --> 29:11.950 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: The
Environmental Defense Fund has
spearheaded multiple studies on
methane

29:11.950 --> 29:17.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
emissions. Its energy policy
manager says the problem is not
a tough one to solve.

29:17.990 --> 29:20.359 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON GOLDSTEIN, Environmental
Defense Fund: Literally, the
problem is being looked at

29:20.359 --> 29:26.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by rocket scientists. But the
solutions are largely plumbing.
We are talking about fixing

29:26.565 --> 29:30.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pipes, stopping them from
leaking at natural gas
production sites, and that's
stuff that

29:30.569 --> 29:32.504 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we know how to do.

29:32.504 --> 29:35.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TOM MULLINS, CEO, Synergy
Operating, LLC: Anywhere that we
have methane usage, you would

29:35.273 --> 29:38.210 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be concerned if you have leaks.

29:38.210 --> 29:42.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: Industry is
hunting and fixing methane
emissions, says Tom Mullins,

29:42.881 --> 29:47.853 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who owns part of an oil and gas
company in Farmington. We met on
the campus of San Juan

29:47.853 --> 29:52.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
College's School of Energy,
which offers hands-on training.

29:52.424 --> 29:56.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM MULLINS: We have been
applying technology, you know,
identifying leaks that are out
there.

29:56.194 --> 30:02.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, we do that on a daily
basis, as all good industry
folks would do.

30:02.100 --> 30:08.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: For industry,
doing green is nice. Seeing
green is even better. Captured

30:08.707 --> 30:12.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
methane can be sold, since it's
essentially natural gas. That's
good for companies and

30:12.944 --> 30:15.113 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
taxpayers.

30:15.113 --> 30:18.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM MULLINS: We're in the
business of producing methane,
and we would like to get paid
for

30:18.950 --> 30:24.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it, and we would like the public
to get paid for their share of
that methane. Here in New

30:24.823 --> 30:29.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mexico, the -- basically the
entire public school system,
both at K-12 and then the higher

30:29.795 --> 30:35.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
educational system, is funded
from the revenues from oil and
gas royalties.

30:35.500 --> 30:42.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: The desire to
recoup emissions has sparked
technological innovations. Jason

30:42.240 --> 30:46.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Libersky's company, Quantigy
Engineering, designs compressors
that vacuum vapors off

30:46.778 --> 30:49.081 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
storage tanks.

30:49.081 --> 30:54.319 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JASON LIBERSKY, CEO, Quantigy
Engineering: What we do now is
basically provide suction

30:54.319 --> 30:56.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to these tanks that just suck
off the gases that would be
normally be released to the

30:56.988 --> 30:58.290 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
atmosphere.

30:58.290 --> 31:00.559 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: And so this
essentially is a vacuum cleaner?

31:00.559 --> 31:01.993 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JASON LIBERSKY: Exactly, a
high-dollar vacuum cleaner.

31:01.993 --> 31:04.129 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

31:04.129 --> 31:10.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: That vacuum
can cost upwards of $50,000.
Infrared cameras can be twice

31:10.168 --> 31:16.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that. Even this tiny control
valve has a stiff price tag for
small producers.

31:16.575 --> 31:22.914 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TOM MULLINS: The little item is
a $400 item, so you can see that
this items has -- there's

31:22.914 --> 31:28.653 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
two of those on this particular
unit, so that's an $800 item.
Some of our marginal type wells

31:28.653 --> 31:33.458 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
might not make $800
profit in a year.

31:33.458 --> 31:38.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: Oil and gas
prices are low right now. But
natural gas production

31:38.230 --> 31:43.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the U.S. is on the upswing,
and is expected to grow more
than 50 percent over the next

31:43.602 --> 31:47.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
25 years. That means emissions
are likely to increase, too,
unless measures are taken

31:47.773 --> 31:50.308 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to reduce them.

31:50.308 --> 31:56.948 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Last year, Colorado, New
Mexico's neighbor to the north,
became the first state to clamp

31:56.948 --> 32:03.288 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
down on methane emissions. Now
federal rules are in the works.
Proposed EPA standards,

32:03.288 --> 32:09.461 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when combined with other federal
actions, could cut emissions
from 2012 levels by 40

32:09.461 --> 32:17.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to 45 percent by the year 2025
and require semi-annual
inspections of production
facilities.

32:17.102 --> 32:22.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Bureau of Land Management,
which oversees public lands,
mostly in the West, has drafted

32:22.307 --> 32:27.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a new rule aimed at reducing
wasteful flaring, venting and
leaking of natural gas. But the

32:27.579 --> 32:31.483 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
details and timetable
aren't known yet.

32:31.483 --> 32:33.885 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Industry doesn't want
more regulation.

32:33.885 --> 32:39.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WALLY DRANGMEISTER: A good
example might be something like
the fact that they call for

32:39.624 --> 32:44.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
using of infrared cameras many
times a year on every well.
Well, that's something that

32:44.362 --> 32:48.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
could cause low-producing wells
that are late in their life to
just become uneconomical

32:48.166 --> 32:53.371 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and have to plugged.

32:53.371 --> 32:57.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Environmentalists say the EPA
proposals are a good start, but
don't go far enough.

32:57.576 --> 33:01.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRUCE BAIZEL: It wouldn't cover
a well like this because it's --
this is an existing well.

33:01.279 --> 33:05.116 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It will only cover new wells.
But you have got to get some
kind of regulation in place

33:05.116 --> 33:09.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the first instance, and I'm
real glad they're doing that.

33:09.387 --> 33:12.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: Still, no
matter the method, cutting
methane emissions is a goal
shared

33:12.791 --> 33:16.361 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
by industry, government
and environmentalists.

33:16.361 --> 33:20.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JON GOLDSTEIN: If you are
concerned about climate change,
it's important for those
reasons.

33:20.432 --> 33:23.435 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you're concerned about waste
of a natural resource, it's
important for those reasons

33:23.435 --> 33:26.104 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as well. It's really
a win-win issue.

33:26.104 --> 33:29.107 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN MCCLEERY: I'm Kathleen
McCleery, for the "PBS NewsHour"
in New Mexico's San

33:29.107 --> 33:33.812 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Juan Basin.

33:33.812 --> 33:44.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Now: the elusive
goal of peace in the Middle
East.

33:44.689 --> 33:47.559 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Two decades ago, there
was a moment of hope.

33:47.559 --> 33:51.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, as chief foreign affairs
correspondent Margaret Warner
reports, the assassination

33:51.429 --> 33:55.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that shattered that momentum
still resonates today.

33:55.600 --> 34:01.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: One hundred
thousand people swelled the
crowd at a Tel Aviv peace rally

34:01.206 --> 34:06.244 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
200 years ago tonight, as Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin took the
microphone to speak.

34:06.244 --> 34:07.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
YITZHAK RABIN, Israeli Prime
Minister (through translator):
We know how to make peace, and

34:07.846 --> 34:10.215 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
not just sing about peace.

34:10.215 --> 34:14.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: But minutes
later, he was fatally gunned
down by a 27-year-old Jewish

34:14.819 --> 34:20.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ultra-nationalist opposed to his
peace efforts with the
Palestinians.

34:20.358 --> 34:25.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rabin was nearing the end of a
reelection campaign and pressing
forward with peace initiatives

34:25.063 --> 34:32.671 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on several fronts. He'd already
signed the historic Oslo accords
in Washington in 1993,

34:32.671 --> 34:35.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
famously shaking hands with
Yasser Arafat, head the
Palestine Liberation
Organization,

34:35.607 --> 34:37.776 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
or PLO.

34:37.776 --> 34:42.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For the first time, Israelis and
Palestinians agreed to
acknowledge each other's right
to

34:42.480 --> 34:44.582 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
exist.

34:44.582 --> 34:51.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YITZHAK RABIN: We, who have
fought against you, the
Palestinians, we say to you
today,

34:51.623 --> 34:58.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in a loud and a clear voice,
enough of blood and tears,
enough.

34:58.964 --> 35:01.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(APPLAUSE)

35:01.433 --> 35:06.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: A year later,
Rabin signed yet another
historic agreement, this one
with

35:06.504 --> 35:12.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
King Hussein of Jordan, to
normalize relations between the
two countries. His actions
stirred

35:12.043 --> 35:16.348 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
a fierce backlash from
right-wing Israelis and Jewish
settlers, who saw them as steps

35:16.348 --> 35:20.318 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
toward forfeiting the
occupied territories.

35:20.318 --> 35:26.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The vilification of Rabin came
despite his war hero background;
27 years a soldier, he

35:26.558 --> 35:32.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
began with an elite Jewish
strike force in the 1940s. And
after Israel's founding in

35:32.530 --> 35:38.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
1948, he rose through the ranks
to become the military's chief
of staff.

35:38.269 --> 35:43.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Rabin went on to oversee
Israel's victory in the 1967
war, winning control of
Jerusalem,

35:43.775 --> 35:50.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the West Bank, and Gaza. As
defense minister in 1987, he put
down the first Palestinian

35:50.315 --> 35:56.554 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
intifada, instructing his troops
to use -- quote -- "force,
power, and blows."

35:56.554 --> 36:01.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was elected prime minister
twice, first in 1974 and then
again in 1992, campaigning

36:01.993 --> 36:04.763 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on the possibility of peace.

36:04.763 --> 36:10.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
YITZHAK RABIN: I believe that
within six to nine months, it
will be possible to reach

36:10.168 --> 36:15.306 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
an agreement with the
Palestinian delegation about
establishment of autonomy.

36:15.306 --> 36:21.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: That vision was
praised at his funeral attended
by 80 heads of state,

36:21.713 --> 36:24.949 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
including Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, President Bill
Clinton, and King Hussein of

36:24.949 --> 36:27.318 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Jordan.

36:27.318 --> 36:32.724 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HUSSEIN BIN TALAL, King of
Jordan: He had courage. He had
vision, and he had a commitment

36:32.724 --> 36:40.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to peace. And standing here, I
commit before you, before my
people in Jordan, before the

36:40.298 --> 36:51.810 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
world, myself to continue to do
my utmost to ensure that we
leave a similar legacy.

36:51.810 --> 36:57.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: But within six
months, right-wing party leader
Benjamin Netanyahu became prime

36:57.582 --> 37:02.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
minister after campaigning on a
promise not to hand back
captured land to Arabs. He began

37:02.420 --> 37:07.258 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a second stint as prime
minister in 2009.

37:07.258 --> 37:13.765 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All post-Rabin efforts to forge
peace encouraged by the United
States have foundered. Last

37:13.765 --> 37:18.470 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
weekend, Israelis marked the
assassination anniversary with a
memorial rally in what

37:18.470 --> 37:23.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is now Rabin Square in Tel Aviv.
Thousands attended, including
former Israeli President

37:23.441 --> 37:26.744 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Shimon Peres and former
President Clinton.

37:26.744 --> 37:30.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BILL CLINTON, Former President
of the United States: The next
step will be determined by

37:30.148 --> 37:38.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whether you decide that Yitzhak
Rabin was right, that you have
to share the future with

37:38.490 --> 37:43.728 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
your neighbors, that you have to
give their children a chance,
too, that you have to stand

37:43.728 --> 37:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for peace, that the risks for
peace are not as severe as the
risk of walking away from

37:48.366 --> 37:51.002 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

37:51.002 --> 37:56.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: But with a new
wave of Palestinian-Israeli
violence under way, it's not
clear that anyone

37:56.307 --> 37:59.077 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
will take that risk
any time soon.

37:59.077 --> 38:02.547 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
For the "PBS NewsHour,"
I'm Margaret Warner.

38:02.547 --> 38:08.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: We look at Rabin's
legacy today two, decades later,
with Dennis Ross, a longtime

38:08.887 --> 38:14.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Middle East peace envoy, who
served in Republican and
Democratic administrations,
Daoud Kuttab,

38:14.959 --> 38:20.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a Palestinian journalist based
in Amman, Jordan, and Ari
Shavit, an Israeli columnist and
author.

38:20.465 --> 38:25.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ari Shavit, 20 years later, do
you wonder whether things could
have been different had

38:25.737 --> 38:28.706 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Yitzhak Rabin not been killed?

38:28.706 --> 38:31.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ARI SHAVIT, Author, "My Promised
Land: The Triumph and Tragedy of
Israel": Yes, I think

38:31.409 --> 38:34.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there is a chance they would
have been different, but I think
that the romantic approach that

38:34.946 --> 38:39.517 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we would have had a perfect
ideal peace is somewhat flawed.

38:39.517 --> 38:45.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let me say, first of all, as an
Israeli, that Rabin's murder is
a traumatic experience in

38:45.890 --> 38:51.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
our nation's history. In the
way, it's a combination of the
murder of Abe Lincoln, John
Kennedy,

38:51.162 --> 38:54.699 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and Martin Luther King.

38:54.699 --> 39:01.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rabin wasn't a saint. He wasn't
a sacred man. He had flaws. But
he had an amazing -- he

39:01.306 --> 39:07.512 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
wasn't only courageous,
intelligent, and authentic
person, but he really tried to
end the conflict,

39:07.512 --> 39:12.750 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the tragedy of the conflict. And
he represented a benign, decent,
benevolent Israel, something

39:12.750 --> 39:15.753 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we all yearn for so much today.

39:15.753 --> 39:19.724 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Daoud Kuttab, what
of that do you accept and what
do you reject?

39:19.724 --> 39:25.363 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAOUD KUTTAB, Palestinian
Journalist: Mr. Rabin was -- as
Ari said, was no angel. He

39:25.363 --> 39:32.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was the person who spoke very
toughly and acted very toughly
against the Palestinian

39:32.337 --> 39:36.808 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
intifada. He encouraged the
soldiers to break the arms of
stone throwers.

39:36.808 --> 39:44.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was a very tough military
man, but he did see -- did
clearly make a conversion in his

39:44.616 --> 39:49.954 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
last days, and he was really
interested in trying to find a
peaceful solution. And he

39:49.954 --> 39:54.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had that combination of a
security man that has been
converted and understood the
needs

39:54.225 --> 39:58.062 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for a political resolution
to the conflict.

39:58.062 --> 40:05.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In that sense, I think he was a
rare species that we do not see
in these days in the
negotiations

40:05.436 --> 40:08.072 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
between Israelis
and Palestinians.

40:08.072 --> 40:13.111 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Dennis Ross, you
wrote in an op-ed peace in The
Los Angeles Times that the last

40:13.111 --> 40:18.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thing that Dennis -- that, I
mean, Yitzhak Rabin said to you
was, "Dennis, expect anything."

40:18.716 --> 40:22.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Twenty years later, what did you
expect that was fulfilled and
what did you expect that

40:22.153 --> 40:24.088 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
wasn't?

40:24.088 --> 40:28.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DENNIS ROSS, Former U.S. Envoy
to Middle East: Well, 20 years
ago, I didn't believe, A, that

40:28.559 --> 40:33.097 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he could be assassinated,
because I had a very hard time
fathoming that Yitzhak Rabin,

40:33.097 --> 40:38.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who was the embodiment of the
Israeli experience, who fought
his whole life for Israel, was

40:38.202 --> 40:42.940 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
someone who could be
assassinated by an Israeli,
number one.

40:42.940 --> 40:48.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Number two, had I been able to
fathom that, I wouldn't have
believed that, 20 years from

40:48.680 --> 40:53.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that moment, we would be where
we are today. I would have
believed that, somehow, even

40:53.017 --> 40:58.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if we didn't have an agreement,
we would have found some kind of
greater basis for coexistence,

40:58.456 --> 41:02.960 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
some kind of greater basis for
separation of these two peoples.

41:02.960 --> 41:07.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are, after all, two
national movements competing for
the same space. And I suspect

41:07.965 --> 41:14.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that some kind of greater basis
of stability between the two --
to be fair, I also didn't

41:14.906 --> 41:19.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
expect that we would be seeing
within the Middle East as a
whole a breakdown of the

41:19.143 --> 41:23.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
state system, Arab states
themselves being really put at
risk.

41:23.748 --> 41:26.150 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The region as a whole is not
what I expected at that point,
certainly, when I was thinking

41:26.150 --> 41:28.586 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
back 20 years ago.

41:28.586 --> 41:33.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Ari Shavit, as you
look back and you look forward,
do you see -- do you think

41:33.091 --> 41:36.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that Israelis believe anymore,
just in general -- I know you
can't speak for everyone -- that

41:36.861 --> 41:39.931 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a two-state solution
is possible?

41:39.931 --> 41:46.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ARI SHAVIT: I think that most
Israelis still want a two-state
way. They want to move forward.

41:46.604 --> 41:50.074 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They want some sort of peace.

41:50.074 --> 41:55.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But they are traumatized by the
failures of all the previous
attempts to bring about a

41:55.680 --> 42:01.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
comprehensive, complete,
idyllic, utopian peace. And in
this sense, the Rabin legacy,

42:01.252 --> 42:07.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so to speak, is really relevant,
because Rabin wasn't a utopian.
The fact that he was a general,

42:07.291 --> 42:13.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he was tough, he was a skeptic,
he was -- he didn't come with a
kind of Mother Teresa approach

42:13.464 --> 42:18.236 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the conflict, that gave him a
lot of credibility within
Israel.

42:18.236 --> 42:23.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think that would have
given him the ability to deal
much better with the conflict.

42:23.141 --> 42:28.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in a sense, what we need
today in Israel is a Rabin-like
of leadership, because the

42:28.479 --> 42:33.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
right went -- became an extreme
right, and the left endured some
sort of romantic view

42:33.918 --> 42:38.122 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of peace, which most
Israelis do not buy.

42:38.122 --> 42:42.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Daoud Kuttab, that's
a tall order that Ari Shavit
just laid out there.

42:42.560 --> 42:47.632 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
From the Palestinian point of
view, where is the leadership
coming from, and does it

42:47.632 --> 42:52.270 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- can it -- can it achieve what
we just heard outlined there, or
is that even something

42:52.270 --> 42:54.238 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
you want?

42:54.238 --> 42:59.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAOUD KUTTAB: My generation
might still be interested in a
two-state solution, but my

42:59.644 --> 43:03.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
son and their generation,
they're not interested in
two-state solution.

43:03.815 --> 43:11.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They look at us as being stupid
and being fooled by the Israelis
who kept us going for

43:11.122 --> 43:14.592 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a long time, and at the same
time they were building Jewish
settlements. I mean, since

43:14.592 --> 43:18.930 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rabin's death, we have had twice
or three times the size of the
Jewish settlements.

43:18.930 --> 43:22.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So they're saying there should
just be one state, and we should
find some kind of a solution

43:22.733 --> 43:28.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where there is equal rights for
everybody. So there is a big
problem right now among

43:28.339 --> 43:34.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Palestinians, in the fact that
they feel that the idea of
two-state solution was just a

43:34.512 --> 43:40.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
farce, and that we were giving
too many opportunities for this
idea of peace talks, and they
went

43:40.384 --> 43:43.721 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
nowhere. Yet we were losing
our land in the meanwhile.

43:43.721 --> 43:46.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Dennis Ross, you
have been at more of these
negotiation tables than you

43:46.924 --> 43:52.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can probably count. Do you
harbor any hope or expectation
of interests converging? And

43:52.763 --> 43:56.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
does the U.S. play a
role in that anymore?

43:56.000 --> 44:01.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DENNIS ROSS: I'm pessimistic in
the near term, because, in a
sense, what Daoud just described

44:01.939 --> 44:08.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as a reality on the Palestinian
side in some ways is mirrored by
the Israelis side, not

44:08.946 --> 44:12.116 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the sense of wanting a
one-state outcome, but in the
level of disbelief that exists

44:12.116 --> 44:15.720 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on the part of both populations.

44:15.720 --> 44:19.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Israelis don't believe that the
Palestinians will ever accept a
two-state outcome that

44:19.290 --> 44:24.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
accepts Israel as a state of the
Jewish people. Palestinians
don't believe that Israelis will

44:24.395 --> 44:29.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ever accept a genuinely
independent Palestinian state.
And the starting point has to be
change

44:29.300 --> 44:33.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the realities on the ground,
begin to restore a level of
belief on each side that shows

44:33.938 --> 44:37.241 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that a two-state outcome
actually could be possible.

44:37.241 --> 44:41.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the U.S. can play a
role, but I also think one of
the things that's going to have

44:41.279 --> 44:45.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to change, given the weakness
and dysfunction on the
Palestinian side, I think that
the

44:45.917 --> 44:49.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Arab states are going to have to
play a different kind of role.
They're going to have to play

44:49.120 --> 44:54.492 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a role where they provide a kind
of cover for Palestinians to be
able to make adjustments

44:54.492 --> 44:59.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or compromises, and they also
provide a response to the
Israelis, where the Israelis
feel,

44:59.697 --> 45:04.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if they make basic compromises
or concessions towards the
Palestinians, the reciprocation

45:04.268 --> 45:08.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will come as much, if not more,
from the Arabs than it will come
from the Palestinians.

45:08.873 --> 45:11.976 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's a tall order, and,
basically, I don't think many in
the region right now are looking

45:11.976 --> 45:15.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at the U.S. administration to be
able to manage something like
that.

45:15.079 --> 45:18.849 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Dennis Ross, Daoud
Kuttab, and Ari Shavit, thank
you all for sharing with

45:18.849 --> 45:23.421 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
us.

45:23.421 --> 45:33.864 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Maybe
you can go home again.

45:33.864 --> 45:38.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Actor Jeff Daniels did it, and
even built his own professional
theater company.

45:38.135 --> 45:41.138 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown visited Daniels
in his Michigan hometown.

45:41.138 --> 45:43.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ACTRESS: He's going to insist
that, if you want the part, you
either audition together

45:43.507 --> 45:46.010 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or go home.

45:46.010 --> 45:50.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In the new play
"Casting Session," two actors
vying for the same role,
desperate

45:50.247 --> 45:54.285 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for any role, await
their auditions.

45:54.285 --> 45:58.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The playwright is Hollywood and
Broadway actor Jeff Daniels,
who's known both the highs and

45:58.389 --> 46:00.858 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
lows of his profession.

46:00.858 --> 46:06.130 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFF DANIELS, Actor/Playwright:
I have been in this waiting room
where you're just trying

46:06.130 --> 46:11.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to get the next gig, the next
job that pays $125 a week, and
maybe someone will come and

46:11.035 --> 46:13.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see it and maybe get you a
better job, but got to get this
one.

